e private plans. The 31-day rule is a key operational requirement that shapes the urgency and planning needed by departing employees. [Data: Entities (45), Relationships (70)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"No health questions are required during the portability process\",\n            \"explanation\": \"One of the most significant features of the portability process is that no health-related questions are asked when converting or porting coverage. This ensures that individuals are not denied coverage or charged higher premiums based on their medical history. This feature is especially important for protecting vulnerable populations, including those with chronic illnesses or prior hospitalizations. The absence of health underwriting supports equitable access to insurance during life transitions. [Data: Entities (47), Relationships (72)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Ported coverage is priced using age-banded group rates\",\n            \"explanation\": \"After portability is applied, the individual policy is priced using age-banded group rates, which categorize premiums based on age brackets rather than individual health status. This pricing model ensures that individuals are not penalized for poor health, but instead pay premiums that reflect their age group. This structure promotes fairness and predictability in cost, making long-term coverage more accessible. It also aligns with the broader goal of maintaining affordability and stability in post-employment insurance. [Data: Entities (42), Relationships (69)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Portability is directly tied to employee transition from group plans\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The portability process is specifically designed for employees who are leaving their employment and losing access to group insurance. The relationship between portability and the employee is foundational, as it enables the individual to retain the same coverage